el Time and Target Years: On the End of Time in IPCC Futures -- tChapter 12. Encountering the Geological Live: Temporalization in the Age of Natural Media -- tConclusion -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2fd2star  aAs climate change becomes an increasingly important part of public discourse, the relationship between time in nature and history is changing. Nature can no longer be considered a slow and immobile background to human history, and the future can no longer be viewed as open and detached from the past. Times of History, Times of Nature engages with this historical shift in temporal sensibilities through a combination of detailed case studies and synthesizing efforts. Focusing on the history of knowledge, media theory, and environmental humanities, this volume explores the rich and nuanced notions of time and temporality that have emerged in response to climate change.  afunded by Riksbankens Jubileumsfond  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aChange. 0aHistoryxPeriodization. 0aHuman ecologyxHistoriography. 0aNatural historyxPhilosophy. 0aTimexHistory. 0aTimexPhilosophy. 7aHISTORY / Modern / General.2bisacsh1 aBergwik, Staffan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBergwik, Staffan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBjærke, Marit Ruge, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEkström, Anders, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEkström, Anders, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHolmberg, Gustav, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIsberg, Erik, econtribut